**1. Purpose & Scope**

This Architecture Decision Record (ADR) documents the significant
technical choices made for FamLink\'s MVP build. Each decision captures
the options considered, the choice made, and the reasoning behind it.
These decisions collectively define the technical foundation that all
development --- including AI-assisted Cursor prompts --- will be built
upon.

This document should be read alongside the PRD. Where the PRD defines
what to build and for whom, the ADR defines how to build it. Together
they are the two source-of-truth documents that govern every development
decision.

**How to Read This Document**

  --------------- -------------------------------------------------------
  **Status        **Meaning**
  Badge**         

  LOCKED          Decision is final for MVP. Do not revisit without a
                  documented reason.

  LOCKED ---      Final for MVP, but explicitly planned for re-evaluation
  REVISIT PHASE 2 at Phase 2.

  OPEN            Decision not yet made. Blocks development until
                  resolved.

  DEFERRED        Not needed for MVP. Will be decided before the relevant
                  phase begins.
  --------------- -------------------------------------------------------

**2. Architecture Overview**

FamLink is a three-tier web and mobile application with an AI layer that
is architecturally first-class --- not bolted on. The high-level system
is:

  ---------------- --------------------------- ------------------------------
  **Layer**        **Components**              **Role**

  Client           React web app + React       User interface across all
                   Native mobile app (Expo)    personas and devices

  API              Node.js / Express REST      Business logic, auth, data
                   API + WebSocket server      access, AI orchestration

  AI Layer         LLM abstraction (Vercel AI  Family assistant, suggestions,
                   SDK) + Tool registry +      agentic actions
                   Context assembler           

  Data             PostgreSQL (primary) +      All persistent data; family
                   Redis (cache/sessions)      graph modeled relationally

  Services         Clerk (auth) + SendGrid     External integrations for
                   (email) + Twilio (SMS) +    identity and notifications
                   FCM (push)                  

  Infrastructure   Vercel (frontend) + Railway Hosting, CDN, storage
                   (backend) + Cloudflare R2   
                   (media, Phase 2)            
  ---------------- --------------------------- ------------------------------

*Principle: Every component chosen is mainstream, well-documented, and
well-supported by AI coding tools. Exotic or niche choices are
explicitly avoided at MVP stage.*

**3. Architecture Decisions**

**ADR-01 Frontend Framework**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-01**      **Frontend Framework**                           **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **React (TypeScript) --- web application built   
                  with Next.js 14 (App Router)**                   

  **Rationale**   React is the dominant frontend framework with    
                  the largest ecosystem, the best AI coding tool   
                  support, and the most available talent. Next.js  
                  adds server-side rendering, API routes, and      
                  file-based routing out of the box. TypeScript is 
                  mandatory --- it prevents an entire class of     
                  runtime errors that are especially costly in an  
                  AI-assisted build workflow where code is         
                  generated at speed. The App Router (Next.js 14+) 
                  is the current mainstream standard and aligns    
                  with where the ecosystem is heading.             
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Key Conventions**

-   TypeScript strict mode enabled across the entire codebase

-   Tailwind CSS for styling --- utility-first, no custom CSS framework

-   shadcn/ui for component library --- accessible, unstyled, fully
    owned in codebase

-   React Query (TanStack Query) for server state management

-   Zustand for client-side state --- lightweight, simple, AI-tool
    friendly

**Options Considered & Rejected**

  --------------------- -------------------------------------------------
  **Option**            **Reason Rejected**

  Vue.js / Nuxt         Smaller ecosystem; less AI tool support; harder
                        to find Cursor examples

  SvelteKit             Excellent framework but niche relative to React
                        at this stage

  Plain React (no       Loses SSR, API routes, and deployment simplicity
  Next.js)              that Next.js provides for free

  Angular               Over-engineered for this use case; steep learning
                        curve for AI-assisted dev
  --------------------- -------------------------------------------------

**ADR-02 Mobile Strategy**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-02**      **Mobile Strategy**                              **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **React Native with Expo --- shared codebase     
                  targeting iOS and Android**                      

  **Rationale**   FamLink must be a mobile-first product. The      
                  Organizer, Grandparent, and Co-Parent personas   
                  all primarily live on their phones. Expo         
                  provides the fastest path to a                   
                  production-quality React Native app without      
                  requiring native build tooling knowledge ---     
                  critical for an AI-assisted small team. The      
                  React / React Native code-sharing story is       
                  imperfect but meaningful: shared types, business 
                  logic, API clients, and design tokens across web 
                  and mobile reduces total codebase size. Expo\'s  
                  managed workflow and EAS (Expo Application       
                  Services) handles App Store and Play Store       
                  deployment without a native developer on the     
                  team.                                            
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Key Conventions**

-   Expo managed workflow for MVP --- eject to bare workflow only if a
    native module requires it

-   Expo Router for navigation --- file-based routing mirrors Next.js
    conventions

-   Shared design tokens and types in a /packages/shared directory

-   React Native Paper or NativeWind (Tailwind for RN) for styling
    consistency

-   Expo EAS for build and OTA update delivery

**Mobile-Specific Persona Requirements**

  --------------- ------------- ------------------------------------------
  **Persona**     **Mobile      **Key Requirements**
                  Priority**    

  Organizer       High          Fast event creation, push notifications,
                                dashboard overview

  Grandparent     High          Large text mode, simple navigation,
                                minimal steps to key info

  Co-Parent       High          Calendar view, schedule visibility,
                                notification reliability

  Reluctant       None          Never requires the app --- email/SMS only
  Member                        participation
  --------------- ------------- ------------------------------------------

**ADR-03 Backend Framework**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-03**      **Backend Framework**                            **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **Node.js with Express (TypeScript) --- REST API 
                  with WebSocket support via Socket.io**           

  **Rationale**   Node.js/Express is the highest-supported backend 
                  stack in AI coding tools and has the largest     
                  available reference codebase for Cursor to draw  
                  on. TypeScript throughout maintains type safety  
                  end-to-end. Express is intentionally minimal --- 
                  it adds structure without imposing opinion,      
                  which keeps the AI-generated code legible and    
                  consistent. Socket.io is added specifically to   
                  support real-time features required by the AI    
                  assistant layer (streaming AI responses) and     
                  future chat functionality. A GraphQL layer is    
                  explicitly deferred --- REST is simpler to       
                  build, debug, and prompt-engineer at MVP stage.  
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**API Structure**

-   RESTful resource-based routing: /api/v1/families, /api/v1/events,
    /api/v1/members, etc.

-   Versioned from day one (/api/v1/) to allow non-breaking changes

-   JWT-based authentication via Clerk --- no custom auth logic

-   Zod for request/response validation --- schema-first,
    TypeScript-native

-   Prisma ORM for all database access --- type-safe, excellent AI tool
    support

**AI-Specific Backend Routes**

-   /api/v1/assistant/chat --- streaming chat endpoint for the family AI
    assistant

-   /api/v1/assistant/suggest --- proactive suggestion generation

-   /api/v1/assistant/action --- agentic action execution with
    confirmation flow

**ADR-04 Database Architecture**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-04**      **Database Architecture**                        **LOCKED ---
                                                                   REVISIT PHASE
                                                                   2**

  **Decision**    **PostgreSQL (primary database) + Redis (cache   
                  and session store). Prisma ORM for all access.** 

  **Rationale**   PostgreSQL is the mainstream, production-grade   
                  relational database with the strongest           
                  ecosystem, best AI tool support, and lowest      
                  operational complexity for a small team. The     
                  family relationship graph is modeled             
                  relationally using a nodes-and-edges table       
                  pattern --- sufficient for MVP-scale traversal   
                  (typically 2-3 hops for any family query). Redis 
                  handles session storage, API response caching,   
                  and rate limiting. A native graph database       
                  (Neo4j or AWS Neptune) will be evaluated at      
                  Phase 2 when real query patterns from production 
                  data can inform the decision. Prisma is chosen   
                  as the ORM for its TypeScript-native schema      
                  definition, migration tooling, and strong        
                  Cursor/AI code generation support.               
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Relational Graph Schema Pattern**

The family relationship graph is implemented using three core tables:

  ------------------- ------------------------ ------------------------------
  **Table**           **Purpose**              **Key Columns**

  persons             Individual user/member   id, user_id (nullable), name,
                      records                  dob, profile_data

  relationships       Edges in the family      id, from_person_id,
                      graph                    to_person_id, type, family_id,
                                               created_at

  family_groups       Extended family          id, name, created_by,
                      containers               settings, created_at

  households          Physical living unit     id, family_id, name, address,
                                               created_at

  household_members   Person ↔ Household edges id, household_id, person_id,
                                               role, joined_at

  family_members      Person ↔ Family edges    id, family_id, person_id,
                                               roles\[\], permissions,
                                               joined_at
  ------------------- ------------------------ ------------------------------

**Relationship Type Registry**

Relationship types are stored as an enum in the database and managed via
a seed table. Initial types at MVP:

-   SPOUSE, PARTNER, EX_SPOUSE

-   PARENT, CHILD, STEP_PARENT, STEP_CHILD, ADOPTIVE_PARENT,
    ADOPTIVE_CHILD

-   SIBLING, HALF_SIBLING, STEP_SIBLING

-   GRANDPARENT, GRANDCHILD

-   AUNT_UNCLE, NIECE_NEPHEW, COUSIN

-   CAREGIVER, GUARDIAN, FAMILY_FRIEND

**Phase 2 Graph DB Migration Path**

If graph traversal performance becomes a bottleneck at scale, the
migration path is: (1) introduce Neo4j alongside PostgreSQL, (2) sync
relationship data to Neo4j via a CDC (change data capture) pipeline, (3)
route graph queries to Neo4j while keeping transactional data in
PostgreSQL. This hybrid is achievable without a full rewrite because the
relationship layer is cleanly separated in the Prisma schema from day
one.

**ADR-05 Authentication & Identity**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-05**      **Authentication & Identity**                    **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **Clerk --- managed authentication with social   
                  OAuth (Google, Apple) and email/password**       

  **Rationale**   Authentication is a security-critical,           
                  high-complexity component that should not be     
                  built from scratch under any circumstances for   
                  an MVP. Clerk provides production-grade auth,    
                  social OAuth, user management, session handling, 
                  MFA, and compliance features out of the box. It  
                  integrates natively with Next.js and Expo.       
                  Google and Apple OAuth are required at launch    
                  --- they are the primary onboarding paths for    
                  the Organizer persona. Email/password is         
                  supported as a fallback. Clerk\'s user metadata  
                  system allows FamLink to attach family graph     
                  references to auth identities cleanly.           
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Guest Participation Architecture**

The Reluctant Member persona requires participation without account
creation. This is implemented via a signed token system:

-   Invitations generate a time-limited signed JWT token (24-48 hour
    expiry for event RSVPs, 7 days for family join invitations)

-   Token encodes: invited person ID, event/family ID, permission scope
    (RSVP-only vs. view-only vs. join-pending)

-   Guest endpoints (/api/v1/guest/\*) validate token signature without
    requiring a Clerk session

-   Guest actions (RSVP, view event) are recorded against the person
    record, not a user account

-   Soft upgrade prompt shown after successful guest action --- never
    mandatory

**Minor Profile Handling**

-   Children under 12 have person records but no user accounts

-   Parent/guardian account controls the minor\'s profile, visibility,
    and data

-   Minor person records are flagged is_minor = true in the persons
    table

-   No behavioral tracking, no AI personalization, no direct
    communication to minors

**ADR-06 AI Architecture (Primary Strategic Decision)**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-06**      **AI Architecture**                              **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **Vercel AI SDK for LLM abstraction +            
                  model-agnostic provider routing + three-layer    
                  capability model (Knowledge → Proactive →        
                  Agentic)**                                       

  **Rationale**   AI is a first-class architectural concern in     
                  FamLink --- not a feature addon. The family      
                  assistant is a primary UI paradigm alongside the 
                  calendar and event views. The architecture is    
                  designed to support the full range of AI         
                  capabilities while being model-agnostic (no      
                  vendor lock-in), maintaining strong privacy      
                  controls (family data never leaves the API layer 
                  uncontrolled), and enabling progressive          
                  capability delivery across MVP and subsequent    
                  phases.                                          
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**6.1 AI Capability Model**

FamLink\'s AI is structured in three layers, delivered across phases:

  ----------- ----------- ------------------------ ------------------------------
  **Layer**   **Phase**   **Capabilities**         **Example Interactions**

  Layer 1     MVP         Answers questions about  \'When is Dad\'s birthday?\' /
  Knowledge               family data; natural     \'Who hasn\'t RSVP\'d?\' /
                          language event creation  \'Create a family dinner
                                                   Saturday at 6pm at Mom\'s\'

  Layer 2     Phase 2     Notices patterns and     \'Emma\'s recital is Friday
  Proactive               surfaces suggestions;    --- want to invite the
                          monitors for             grandparents?\' / \'3 people
                          coordination gaps        haven\'t responded to
                                                   Thanksgiving\'

  Layer 3     Phase 3     Takes actions on behalf  \'Send reminders to
  Agentic                 of users with explicit   non-responders\' / \'Find a
                          confirmation; commerce   venue for 20 near Grandma\'s
                          integrations             and book it\' / \'Split the
                                                   catering cost\'
  ----------- ----------- ------------------------ ------------------------------

**6.2 LLM Provider Strategy**

FamLink uses a model-agnostic architecture. The Vercel AI SDK is the
abstraction layer --- it provides a unified interface across OpenAI,
Anthropic, Google, and other providers, allowing model selection and
switching without application code changes.

  ----------------- ------------------------- ----------------------------
  **Provider**      **Recommended Use Case**  **Why**

  Anthropic Claude  Primary assistant model   Strongest
  (claude-sonnet)   at MVP                    instruction-following and
                                              structured output; best for
                                              family context tasks

  OpenAI GPT-4o     Fallback / A-B testing    Fastest, widest tool-calling
                                              support; good for
                                              latency-sensitive
                                              interactions

  OpenAI            High-frequency low-stakes Proactive suggestions,
  GPT-4o-mini /     tasks                     notification drafting ---
  Claude Haiku                                cost efficiency at scale

  Google Gemini     Future multimodal         Photo analysis, voice
                    features                  interaction --- Phase 3+
                                              consideration
  ----------------- ------------------------- ----------------------------

-   Model selection is configurable per request type --- not hardcoded

-   Provider API keys stored in environment variables; never exposed to
    client

-   Usage and cost monitoring via LangSmith or Helicone from day one

**6.3 Context Assembly --- The Family Context Layer**

The quality of every AI interaction depends on giving the model the
right context about the family. A dedicated Context Assembler service is
built into the API layer:

  --------------------- ------------------------ -------------------------
  **Context Component** **What It Provides**     **Example**

  Family graph snapshot Members, relationships,  \"Sarah is married to
                        household groupings      Tom. Their children are
                                                 Emma (8) and Jack (11).\"

  Upcoming events       Next 30 days of family   \"Thanksgiving is Nov 28
                        calendar                 at Grandma\'s. 8 invited,
                                                 5 confirmed.\"

  Pending actions       Unresolved RSVPs,        \"Uncle Dave has not
                        missing info, overdue    responded to 3 events
                        tasks                    this month.\"

  Member preferences    Known preferences,       \"Grandma prefers email
                        dietary restrictions,    reminders. Emma is
                        notes                    vegetarian.\"

  Conversation history  Prior turns in current   Full rolling window of
                        session                  current assistant session
  --------------------- ------------------------ -------------------------

Context assembly follows a budget model --- total token budget per
request is managed to balance richness with cost. High-relevance context
is always included; peripheral context is pruned based on the query
type.

**6.4 Tool Registry --- Agentic Action Framework**

For Layer 2 and Layer 3 capabilities, the AI executes actions via a
structured tool registry. Each tool is a typed function the model can
call, with explicit schemas and confirmation requirements:

  ------------------- --------------------- ---------------- --------------
  **Tool Name**       **Action**            **Confirmation   **Phase**
                                            Required?**      

  create_event        Create a new family   Preview shown,   MVP
                      event                 user confirms    

  send_invitation     Invite members to an  Recipient list   MVP
                      event                 shown, user      
                                            confirms         

  send_reminder       Send reminder to      List shown, user MVP
                      non-responders        confirms         

  update_rsvp         Update RSVP on behalf Always confirms  MVP
                      of user                                

  draft_message       Draft notification or User reviews     MVP
                      message text          before send      

  suggest_event       Proactively propose a Suggestion card  Phase 2
                      new event             shown            

  search_venues       Search for venues via Results shown    Phase 3
                      partner API           for user         
                                            selection        

  make_reservation    Book a venue or       Full             Phase 3
                      service               confirmation     
                                            with cost        

  split_payment       Calculate and request Amounts and      Phase 3
                      cost splits           recipients       
                                            confirmed        
  ------------------- --------------------- ---------------- --------------

Critical guardrail: The AI never executes an action that sends a
communication, spends money, or modifies family data without an explicit
user confirmation step. The propose-confirm pattern is non-negotiable
across all agentic tools.

**6.5 Chat Interface Architecture**

The family assistant is surfaced as a persistent chat interface,
available from any screen in the app. Implementation:

-   Streaming responses via Vercel AI SDK useChat hook --- real-time
    word-by-word display

-   Conversation history persisted in PostgreSQL
    (assistant_conversations, assistant_messages tables)

-   Session context window managed server-side --- client sends session
    ID, server assembles full context

-   Tool call results rendered as structured UI cards inline in the chat
    (event previews, RSVP summaries, etc.)

-   Rate limiting per user per day --- prevents runaway API costs during
    beta

-   Accessible on web and mobile via the same API endpoint

**6.6 Privacy & AI Data Handling**

-   Family data is never sent to LLM providers in a form that includes
    Personally Identifiable Information beyond what is necessary for the
    specific query

-   Production family data is never used for model training --- standard
    API terms with all major providers prohibit this by default

-   All AI interactions are logged server-side for debugging, quality
    review, and abuse detection

-   Users can view and delete their AI conversation history

-   AI features can be disabled at the family group level by the
    Organizer

**ADR-07 Notifications Infrastructure**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-07**      **Notifications Infrastructure**                 **LOCKED**

  **Decision**    **Three-channel notification stack: SendGrid     
                  (email) + Twilio (SMS) + Firebase Cloud          
                  Messaging (push). All three required at MVP.**   

  **Rationale**   The Reluctant Member and Grandparent personas    
                  make notifications architecturally critical ---  
                  not a nice-to-have. Email and SMS are the        
                  primary participation channels for family        
                  members who will never install the app. All      
                  three channels must be production-ready at MVP   
                  launch. A unified Notification Service           
                  abstraction layer routes notifications to the    
                  appropriate channel(s) based on user preferences 
                  and account type.                                
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Notification Service Architecture**

  ------------- -------------- --------------------------- --------------------
  **Channel**   **Provider**   **Use Cases**               **Persona Priority**

  Email         SendGrid       Event invitations, RSVP     Reluctant Member
                               links, weekly digests,      (primary),
                               birthday reminders, account Grandparent
                               management                  (primary), all users

  SMS           Twilio         Event invitations with RSVP Reluctant Member
                               link, day-of reminders,     (primary),
                               urgent family notifications Grandparent
                                                           (secondary)

  Push          Firebase (FCM) Real-time alerts, RSVP      Organizer (primary),
                               received, new event, AI     Co-Parent (primary),
                               assistant suggestions       engaged members
  ------------- -------------- --------------------------- --------------------

**Notification Preferences Model**

-   Each user controls their channel preferences (push, email, SMS)
    independently per notification type

-   Guest/Reluctant Members receive only email + SMS; push requires app
    install and account

-   Grandparent default profile: email + push enabled; SMS optional

-   Digest option: users can opt for a daily or weekly digest email
    instead of individual notifications

-   Organizer receives all channels by default --- she needs maximum
    visibility

-   Unsubscribe and opt-out respected at data layer, not just preference
    flags

**ADR-08 Hosting & Infrastructure**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-08**      **Hosting & Infrastructure**                     **LOCKED ---
                                                                   REVISIT PHASE
                                                                   2**

  **Decision**    **Vercel (Next.js frontend) + Railway (Node.js   
                  API + PostgreSQL + Redis) for MVP. Migrate to    
                  AWS/GCP at scale.**                              

  **Rationale**   The hosting strategy prioritizes speed of        
                  deployment, minimal DevOps overhead, and cost    
                  efficiency at MVP scale. Vercel is the native    
                  deployment platform for Next.js and handles edge 
                  CDN, preview deployments, and zero-config SSL    
                  automatically. Railway provides managed          
                  PostgreSQL and Redis alongside the Node.js API   
                  in a single platform with simple environment     
                  management. Both platforms are well-documented,  
                  widely used, and support the kind of rapid       
                  iteration required in an AI-assisted build       
                  workflow. Infrastructure-as-code and migration   
                  to AWS or GCP is a Phase 2 decision, triggered   
                  when team size or cost efficiency demands it.    
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**Environment Strategy**

  ----------------- ------------------------------ -------------------------
  **Environment**   **Purpose**                    **Deployment Trigger**

  Development       Local developer machines       Manual / local only

  Preview           Per-PR preview deployments     Every pull request ---
                    (Vercel)                       automatic

  Staging           Pre-production validation      Merge to main branch ---
                                                   automatic

  Production        Live product                   Manual promotion from
                                                   staging
  ----------------- ------------------------------ -------------------------

**ADR-09 Real-Time & Chat**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-09**      **Real-Time & Chat**                             **LOCKED ---
                                                                   REVISIT PHASE
                                                                   2**

  **Decision**    **Socket.io for MVP real-time needs (AI          
                  streaming, live RSVP updates). Stream.io for     
                  full family chat in Phase 2.**                   

  **Rationale**   MVP requires real-time capability for two        
                  specific needs: streaming AI assistant responses 
                  (word-by-word), and live RSVP count updates on   
                  the event dashboard. Socket.io handles both      
                  without introducing a separate managed service.  
                  Full family group chat --- a Phase 2 feature --- 
                  will use Stream.io, a managed real-time          
                  messaging platform that handles the complex      
                  requirements of group chat (read receipts,       
                  message history, push integration, moderation)   
                  without building from scratch. Do not build a    
                  chat system from scratch under any               
                  circumstances.                                   
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**ADR-10 Media & File Storage**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-10**      **Media & File Storage**                         **DEFERRED
                                                                   --- Phase 2**

  **Decision**    **Cloudflare R2 for photo and media storage when 
                  photo sharing is built in Phase 2.**             

  **Rationale**   Photo and media sharing is explicitly out of MVP 
                  scope. When built in Phase 2, Cloudflare R2 is   
                  the preferred storage layer: S3-compatible API   
                  (zero code changes if migrating from S3), zero   
                  egress fees (critical for photo-heavy usage      
                  patterns), strong CDN integration via            
                  Cloudflare\'s network, and competitive pricing.  
                  No media infrastructure needs to be built or     
                  provisioned for MVP --- defer entirely.          
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

**ADR-11 Commerce & Payments**

  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------
  **ADR-11**      **Commerce & Payments**                          **DEFERRED
                                                                   --- Phase 3**

  **Decision**    **Stripe for subscriptions and payment           
                  processing. Affiliate commerce via partner APIs  
                  (Amazon, travel, venues) in Phase 3.**           

  **Rationale**   Two distinct payment concerns exist in FamLink:  
                  (1) user subscriptions for the paid tier, and    
                  (2) affiliate/transactional commerce for gifts,  
                  reservations, and event services. Stripe handles 
                  subscriptions from day one of monetization       
                  (post-beta). Affiliate commerce --- where        
                  FamLink earns a commission on family purchases   
                  --- is Phase 3 and requires dedicated partner    
                  API integrations. The AI agentic layer (ADR-06)  
                  is designed with commerce tool hooks built in,   
                  so the commerce capability plugs in without an   
                  architecture change when Phase 3 begins.         
  --------------- ------------------------------------------------ -------------

